VJames Arthur works in the area of mathematics called automorphic representations. These objects date back to the nineteenth century, but in recent years have come to occupy a central place in mathematics known as the Langlands program. The conjectures of Robert Langlands that define the program are still largely unresolved. Roughly speaking, they assert that concrete spectral data wrapped up in automorphic representations govern fundamental processes from quite different domains of mathematics. One of the primary tools for analyzing automorphic representations has been a complex trace formula that relates this spectral data to various kinds of geometric data. It was introduced in special cases by Selberg in 1956, and was then established for general groups by Arthur over the later period from 1975 to 2000. Arthur has used the trace formula to classify certain automorphic representations and establish some cases of the Langlands conjectures. He is now working on the central premise of the Langlands program known as the principle of functoriality.James Arthur works in the area of mathematics called automorphic representations. These objects date back to the nineteenth century, but in recent years have come to occupy a central place in mathematics known as the Langlands program. The conjectures of Robert Langlands that define the program are still largely unresolved. Roughly speaking, they assert that concrete spectral data wrapped up in automorphic representations govern fundamental processes from quite different domains of mathematics. One of the primary tools for analyzing automorphic representations has been a complex trace formula that relates this spectral data to various kinds of geometric data. It was introduced in special cases by Selberg in 1956, and was then established for general groups by Arthur over the later period from 1975 to 2000. Arthur has used the trace formula to classify certain automorphic representations and establish some cases of the Langla