VBonnie Bartel is the Ralph and Dorothy Looney Professor in the Biosciences Department at Rice University. She is a plant geneticist who has dissected regulation of the growth hormone auxin, discovered specific functions of several plant microRNAs, and elucidated the roles, biogenesis, and turnover of plant peroxisomes. Bartel received her B.A. in Biology from Bethel College in North Newton Kansas. She received her Ph.D. in Biology in 1990 from the Massachusetts Institute of Technology, where she held an NSF Graduate Fellowship and studied the yeast ubiquitin system with Alexander Varshavsky. She was an American Cancer Society Postdoctoral Fellow at the Whitehead Institute for Biomedical Research with Gerald Fink, where she began studying auxin metabolism in the reference plant Arabidopsis thaliana. In 1995, Bartel joined the faculty of Rice University. In addition to the National Academy of Sciences, Bartel is a member of the American Academy of Arts and Sciences and is a fellow of the American Association for the Advancement of Science and of the American Society of Plant Biologists.Bonnie Bartel is the Ralph and Dorothy Looney Professor in the Biosciences Department at Rice University. She is a plant geneticist who has dissected regulation of the growth hormone auxin, discovered specific functions of several plant microRNAs, and elucidated the roles, biogenesis, and turnover of plant peroxisomes. Bartel received her B.A. in Biology from Bethel College in North Newton Kansas. She received her Ph.D. in Biology in 1990 from the Massachusetts Institute of Technology, where she held an NSF Graduate Fellowship and studied the yeast ubiquitin system with Alexander Varshavsky. She was an American Cancer Society Postdoctoral Fellow at the Whitehead Institute for Biomedical Research with Gerald Fink, where she began studying auxin metabolism in the reference plant Arabidopsis thaliana. In 1995, Bartel joined the faculty of Rice University. In addition to the National Acade