VUsing varied techniques from algebra, analysis, and geometry, Bhargava addresses basic questions in number theory.  Examples include: when does a positive-definite quadratic form with integer coefficients take every possible positive integer value?  What is the probability that an elliptic curve equation y^2 = x^3 + A x + B has a rational solution (x,y)?  What is the probability that a random integer polynomial of large degree takes a square value?  Bhargava uses such questions as a starting point to study the structure of the integers, higher degree polynomials and forms over the integers, and related arithmetic and geometric objects.Using varied techniques from algebra, analysis, and geometry, Bhargava addresses basic questions in number theory.  Examples include: when does a positive-definite quadratic form with integer coefficients take every possible positive integer value?  What is the probability that an elliptic curve equation y^2 = x^3 + A x + B has a rational solution (x,y)?  What is the probability that a random integer polynomial of large degree takes a square value?  Bhargava uses such questions as a starting point to study the structure of the integers, higher degree polynomials and forms over the integers, and related arithmetic and geometric objects.Using varied techniques from algebra, analysis, and geometry, Bhargava addresses basic questions in number theory.  Examples include: when does a positive-definite quadratic form with integer coefficients take every possible positive integer value?  What is the probability that an elliptic curve equation y^2 = x^3 + A x + B has a rational solution (x,y)?  What is the probability that a random integer polynomial of large degree takes a square value?  Bhargava uses such questions as a starting point to study the structure of the integers, higher degree polynomials and forms over the integers, and related arithmetic and geometric objects.
