VThe research focus of the Coates laboratory is the development of new catalysts for the synthesis of macromolecules as well as fine chemicals. Coates\u2019 research centers on developing new methods for reacting commodity feedstocks (such as alkenes, epoxides, carbon monoxide, and carbon dioxide) in unprecedented ways. Current research focuses on four primary themes, the first of which is the development of homogeneous catalysts for olefin polymerization, heterocycle carbonylation, epoxide homo- and copolymerization, and the utilization of carbon dioxide in polymer synthesis. The second area of interest is the utilization of naturally occurring building blocks such as terpenes, saccharides, and plant-based oils for the synthesis of biodegradable polymers. A third focus area is polymer electrolytes for energy storage (batteries, supercapacitors) as well as energy conversion (hydroxide exchange fuel cells). The fourth area of investigation is the development of materials that allow more efficient recycling of commodity plastics, and promote improved properties of current commercial polymers.The research focus of the Coates laboratory is the development of new catalysts for the synthesis of macromolecules as well as fine chemicals. Coates\u2019 research centers on developing new methods for reacting commodity feedstocks (such as alkenes, epoxides, carbon monoxide, and carbon dioxide) in unprecedented ways. Current research focuses on four primary themes, the first of which is the development of homogeneous catalysts for olefin polymerization, heterocycle carbonylation, epoxide homo- and copolymerization, and the utilization of carbon dioxide in polymer synthesis. The second area of interest is the utilization of naturally occurring building blocks such as terpenes, saccharides, and plant-based oils for the synthesis of biodegradable polymers. A third focus area is polymer electrolytes for energy storage (batteries, supercapacitors) as well as energy conversion (hydrox