VMy laboratory studies how cells and antigens come together to generate immune responses. This involves a focus on deciphering the cues that guide immune cell movements within, and egress from, lymphoid organs. G-protein coupled receptors (GPCRs) are a major class of chemoattractant receptor on immune cells and we have used gain- and loss-of function approaches to establish roles for several GPCRs that respond to protein (chemokine) and lipid (sphingosine-1-phosphate (S1P), endocannabinoid and oxysterol) ligands and to study how these responses adapt after exposure to antigen or inflammatory inputs. We established that lymphocyte egress from lymphoid organs is mediated by S1PR1 and defined enzymatic mechanisms acting to maintain high S1P levels at egress sites. We found CD69 acts a repressor of S1PR1 and we continue to study how this and other egress regulators work. We have a strong interest in understanding how cell interaction dynamics influence the selection events underlying antibody affinity maturation in germinal centers. We use real-time intravital 2-photon microscopy procedures to study these dynamics and are working on tools for the in vivo quantitation of cell-cell interaction and cell signaling in germinal centers. We have also begun exploring requirements for barrier immunity in lymphoid organs and at epithelial surfaces. This includes an interest in the cues guiding cell positioning at these surfaces and the factors required for mounting intestinal IgA antibody responses.My laboratory studies how cells and antigens come together to generate immune responses. This involves a focus on deciphering the cues that guide immune cell movements within, and egress from, lymphoid organs. G-protein coupled receptors (GPCRs) are a major class of chemoattractant receptor on immune cells and we have used gain- and loss-of function approaches to establish roles for several GPCRs that respond to protein (chemokine) and lipid (sphingosine-1-phosphate (S1P), endocannabin