VEric D'Asaro\u2019s research centers on understanding the physics of the upper ocean and its interactions with biogeochemistry. For the past 25 years, his group has designed, built and operated "Lagrangian floats", a new class of robotic oceanographic instruments that accurately follow the three dimensional motion of water parcels, particularly in regions of strong mixing. Tracing the motion of water effectively measures previously inaccessible aspects of turbulence and mixing, while also mimicking the motion of chemical species and plankton, thereby giving unique insights into their dynamics. Different problems can be addressed by equipping the floats with different sensors, and changing, through software, how they respond to their environment. Through a series of multi-investigator field campaigns targeted at specific physical and biogeochemical processes and appropriately combining the floats with other robotic instruments and ships, the group has worked to build and test quantitative models of these phenomena. These continuing efforts target air-sea interactions in hurricanes and typhoons, interactions between surface and internal waves and turbulence, submesoscale and frontal dynamics, oxygen minimum zones and the North Atlantic spring bloom.Eric D'Asaro\u2019s research centers on understanding the physics of the upper ocean and its interactions with biogeochemistry. For the past 25 years, his group has designed, built and operated "Lagrangian floats", a new class of robotic oceanographic instruments that accurately follow the three dimensional motion of water parcels, particularly in regions of strong mixing. Tracing the motion of water effectively measures previously inaccessible aspects of turbulence and mixing, while also mimicking the motion of chemical species and plankton, thereby giving unique insights into their dynamics. Different problems can be addressed by equipping the floats with different sensors, and changing, through software, how they respon