VKatherine H. Freeman is a Professor of Geosciences at The Pennsylvania State University.  She studies fossil biomolecules, or biomarkers, from ancient plants, algae and microbes.  She is known particularly for her work developing methods to analyze stable isotope ratios of biomarkers, and for their application to past climate and biogeochemistry.  Freeman was born in Pullman, Washington in 1962, and grew up in Potomac, Maryland.  She graduated from Wellesley College in 1984, with a dual major in Geology and Classical Civilization.  She earned her doctorate in 1991 in the Geological Sciences from Indiana University, in Bloomington, IN.  She was a postdoctoral scholar at the Skidaway Institute of Oceanography in Savannah Georgia, and joined the faculty at Penn State in 1991.  Freeman is a Fellow of the Geological Society of America, The Canadian Institute for Advanced Research, The Geochemical Society, The American Academy of Microbiology, the American Geophysical Union, and the Guggenheim Foundation.  Freeman is co-Editor of Annual Reviews in Earth and Planetary Sciences, and is Chair of the Organic Geochemistry Division and on the Board of Directors of the Geochemical Society.Katherine H. Freeman is a Professor of Geosciences at The Pennsylvania State University.  She studies fossil biomolecules, or biomarkers, from ancient plants, algae and microbes.  She is known particularly for her work developing methods to analyze stable isotope ratios of biomarkers, and for their application to past climate and biogeochemistry.  Freeman was born in Pullman, Washington in 1962, and grew up in Potomac, Maryland.  She graduated from Wellesley College in 1984, with a dual major in Geology and Classical Civilization.  She earned her doctorate in 1991 in the Geological Sciences from Indiana University, in Bloomington, IN.  She was a postdoctoral scholar at the Skidaway Institute of Oceanography in Savannah Georgia, and joined the faculty at Penn State in 1991.  Freeman is a Fellow