VKen Freeman's research interests are in the formation, dynamics and evolution of galaxies and globular clusters, and in the problem of dark matter in disk galaxies. He was one of the first to point out that spiral galaxies contain a large fraction of dark matter, and he uses optical and radio telescope data and dynamical techniques to learn about the structure and properties of the massive dark halos of spirals and dwarf galaxies. Much of his recent work is in the field of Galactic Archaeology, using the chemical and dynamical properties of stars to unravel the formation history of the Milky Way. He is currently involved in a large high resolution spectroscopic survey (GALAH, on the Anglo Australian Telescope) to measure abundances of about 30 chemical elements in a million stars in the Milky Way.Ken Freeman's research interests are in the formation, dynamics and evolution of galaxies and globular clusters, and in the problem of dark matter in disk galaxies. He was one of the first to point out that spiral galaxies contain a large fraction of dark matter, and he uses optical and radio telescope data and dynamical techniques to learn about the structure and properties of the massive dark halos of spirals and dwarf galaxies. Much of his recent work is in the field of Galactic Archaeology, using the chemical and dynamical properties of stars to unravel the formation history of the Milky Way. He is currently involved in a large high resolution spectroscopic survey (GALAH, on the Anglo Australian Telescope) to measure abundances of about 30 chemical elements in a million stars in the Milky Way.Ken Freeman's research interests are in the formation, dynamics and evolution of galaxies and globular clusters, and in the problem of dark matter in disk galaxies. He was one of the first to point out that spiral galaxies contain a large fraction of dark matter, and he uses optical and radio telescope data and dynamical techniques to learn about the structure and properties of th