VF. Duncan M. Haldane is a condensed matter theorist who is known for work on exotic quantum states of matter, including low-dimensional quantum magnetism and the quantum Hall effect, and their entanglement properties. He shared the 2016 Nobel Prize for Physics for his work on \u201ctopological phases of matter\u201d. Haldane was born in London, England, and graduated from the University of Cambridge with a degree in Physics in 1973, and again in 1978 with a Ph.D. supervised by P. W. Anderson. His initial postdoctoral position was as a physicist at the Institut Laue-Langevin in Grenoble (France), followed by faculty positions at the University of Southern California, University of California San Diego, and Princeton University, as well as a period spent as a Member of Technical Staff at Bell Laboratories. He is also a Fellow of the Royal Society of London.F. Duncan M. Haldane is a condensed matter theorist who is known for work on exotic quantum states of matter, including low-dimensional quantum magnetism and the quantum Hall effect, and their entanglement properties. He shared the 2016 Nobel Prize for Physics for his work on \u201ctopological phases of matter\u201d. Haldane was born in London, England, and graduated from the University of Cambridge with a degree in Physics in 1973, and again in 1978 with a Ph.D. supervised by P. W. Anderson. His initial postdoctoral position was as a physicist at the Institut Laue-Langevin in Grenoble (France), followed by faculty positions at the University of Southern California, University of California San Diego, and Princeton University, as well as a period spent as a Member of Technical Staff at Bell Laboratories. He is also a Fellow of the Royal Society of London.F. Duncan M. Haldane is a condensed matter theorist who is known for work on exotic quantum states of matter, including low-dimensional quantum magnetism and the quantum Hall effect, and their entanglement properties. He shared the 2016 Nobel Prize for Physics for 