VThe disparate plant groups comprising genus Rhododendron have a global distribution that accurately reflects major geologic events of the Cenozoic era, including collision of India with S. Asia, northward movement of the Australian plate and collision of Wrangellia with N. America. Many Rhododendron species inhabit East Asia and the North Pacific rim, while Europe and central regions of North America are relatively species-poor. In recent years, Benjamin Hall\u2019s laboratory has increasingly used DNA sequence data--first of genes, and now of genomes\u2014to answer phylogenetic and biogeographic questions associated with the spread and evolutionary divergence of Rhododendron species in East and SE Asia and in the Pacific Northwest. At present, the clearest evolutionary trajectory is that of Rhododendron subgenus Hymenanthes, a taxon with evergreen, broad smooth leaves. From an origin in NE China, Hymenanthes diversified to about 300 species while spreading southwestward to higher elevation regions in and around the Himalayas. Besides these, there is also a smaller group of basal Hymenanthes species, each of them native to a specific area in Eastern or Western North America, NE Asia, or Asia Minor. Genomic DNA analyses of both the 300 East Asian and the 10 geographically dispersed basal Hymenanthes species reveal the historical interplay between tectonic events and Rhododendron migration and evolution.The disparate plant groups comprising genus Rhododendron have a global distribution that accurately reflects major geologic events of the Cenozoic era, including collision of India with S. Asia, northward movement of the Australian plate and collision of Wrangellia with N. America. Many Rhododendron species inhabit East Asia and the North Pacific rim, while Europe and central regions of North America are relatively species-poor. In recent years, Benjamin Hall\u2019s laboratory has increasingly used DNA sequence data--first of genes, and now of genomes\u2014to answer p