VAlex Halliday is an isotope geochemist who develops mass spectrometry techniques and applies them to the origin and early evolution of the terrestrial planets.  He also conducts studies of mantle melting, magmatic systems, mineral and hydrocarbon deposits, ocean chemistry, continental erosion and the origins of planetary volatiles. Recognising the potential of multiple collector inductively coupled mass spectrometry in particular, his group developed methods for determining precise levels of natural mass dependent fractionation in silicon, vanadium, nickel, tungsten, thallium and uranium, in addition to developing other isotopic systems.  Among diverse discoveries, Halliday and others found, by using the decay of hafnium-182 to tungsten-182, that Earth took tens of millions of years to accrete, culminating in the Moon forming event after more than thirty million years. In contrast asteroidal sized objects and Mars formed within just a few million years. Halliday also demonstrated that silicon is a likely light element in Earth\u2019s core based on the first evidence of metal-silicate isotopic fractionation. He also showed that the oxygen isotopic composition of Earth and Moon are indistinguishable to very high levels of precision providing evidence endorsed by other isotopic systems, that the Moon\u2019s atoms were derived from, or equilibrated with, those of Earth.Alex Halliday is an isotope geochemist who develops mass spectrometry techniques and applies them to the origin and early evolution of the terrestrial planets.  He also conducts studies of mantle melting, magmatic systems, mineral and hydrocarbon deposits, ocean chemistry, continental erosion and the origins of planetary volatiles. Recognising the potential of multiple collector inductively coupled mass spectrometry in particular, his group developed methods for determining precise levels of natural mass dependent fractionation in silicon, vanadium, nickel, tungsten, thallium and uranium, in addition to 