VDennis L. Hartmann works on a broad range of subjects within the atmospheric sciences, particularly focused on variability and change of Earth\u2019s climate. A strong focus has been natural variability that originates in the climate system associated with eddy-jet interactions in the troposphere and stratosphere. Eddy-jet interactions in the troposphere give rise to large-amplitude, low-frequency variability in westerly winds that have significant effects on the stratosphere above and the ocean below. Another focus of research is the effect of clouds on Earth\u2019s radiative energy balance and on climate change. Cloud tops tend to rise to keep a relatively constant temperature as the climate warms, especially in the Tropics, which results in a positive longwave cloud feedback, making surface temperature more sensitive to natural or human-caused climate forcing. A negative climate feedback can result when ice clouds at high latitudes convert to liquid water in a warmed climate. The changed heating gradient associated with more reflective liquid clouds in high latitudes can induce an increase in westerly wind speed in middle latitudes, thus coupling the microphysics of clouds to the global circulation of the atmosphere.Dennis L. Hartmann works on a broad range of subjects within the atmospheric sciences, particularly focused on variability and change of Earth\u2019s climate. A strong focus has been natural variability that originates in the climate system associated with eddy-jet interactions in the troposphere and stratosphere. Eddy-jet interactions in the troposphere give rise to large-amplitude, low-frequency variability in westerly winds that have significant effects on the stratosphere above and the ocean below. Another focus of research is the effect of clouds on Earth\u2019s radiative energy balance and on climate change. Cloud tops tend to rise to keep a relatively constant temperature as the climate warms, especially in the Tropics, which results in a posi