VEdward Hoover\u2019s laboratory focuses on the pathogenesis and intervention for retrovirus and prion infections--in particular feline leukemia virus (FeLV), the feline and simian immunodeficiency viruses (FIV, SIV). As par to this work, his laboratory developed the first successful vaccine for feline leukemia virus, now used worldwide to immunize millions of cats against leukemia. More recently his laboratory has focused on the emergent transmissible prion disease of deer and elk chronic wasting disease (CWD), This transmissible protein misfolding disease is related to bovine spongiform encephalopathy (mad cow disease), human Creutzfeld-Jakob disease, and has mechanisms in common with the major human neurodegenerative diseases (Alzheimer\u2019s, Parkinsons, ALS). Work in Hoover\u2019s laboratory encompasses: (1) the pathways whereby retroviruses and prions cross the mucous membranes and traffic to tissues and cells to initiate infection and disease; (2) the mechanisms involved in shedding and transmission of prions and retroviruses--both from animal to animal and through the environment; (3) the inter-species transmission barriers for prions in animals and humans; (4) new rapid methods for clinical detection of prions and prion-like proteins in living individuals and in the environment; and (5) vaccines for retrovirus and prion infections.Edward Hoover\u2019s laboratory focuses on the pathogenesis and intervention for retrovirus and prion infections--in particular feline leukemia virus (FeLV), the feline and simian immunodeficiency viruses (FIV, SIV). As par to this work, his laboratory developed the first successful vaccine for feline leukemia virus, now used worldwide to immunize millions of cats against leukemia. More recently his laboratory has focused on the emergent transmissible prion disease of deer and elk chronic wasting disease (CWD), This transmissible protein misfolding disease is related to bovine spongiform encephalopathy (mad cow disease), human Cr