VReinhard Jahn's laboratory is interested in the molecular mechanisms of neuronal exocyotosis, with particular emphasis on the conformational transitions during SNARE-mediated membrane fusion and their regulation by accessory proteins such as synaptotagmin, Munc18 and Munc13. To this end, they mainly use structural biochemistry (including crystallography) and artificial membranes to isolate and characterize partial reactions involved in the fusion pathway. Their work was instrumental in developing the zippering hypothesis for SNARE function, which is presently widely accepted. Furthermore, the lab made essential contributions to our understanding of the calcium sensor synaptotagmin that triggers exocytosis of synaptic vesicles in response to stimulation. Moreover, the laboratory developed the first quantitative molecular model of a trafficking organelle, and it clarified how synaptic vesicles can be filled with neurotransmitters within seconds after being endocytosed after use.Reinhard Jahn's laboratory is interested in the molecular mechanisms of neuronal exocyotosis, with particular emphasis on the conformational transitions during SNARE-mediated membrane fusion and their regulation by accessory proteins such as synaptotagmin, Munc18 and Munc13. To this end, they mainly use structural biochemistry (including crystallography) and artificial membranes to isolate and characterize partial reactions involved in the fusion pathway. Their work was instrumental in developing the zippering hypothesis for SNARE function, which is presently widely accepted. Furthermore, the lab made essential contributions to our understanding of the calcium sensor synaptotagmin that triggers exocytosis of synaptic vesicles in response to stimulation. Moreover, the laboratory developed the first quantitative molecular model of a trafficking organelle, and it clarified how synaptic vesicles can be filled with neurotransmitters within seconds after being endocytosed after use.Reinhard Jahn's l