VKlavs F. Jensen is a chemical engineer recognized for his work on reaction engineering. He is particularly known for his studies of chemical vapor deposition and plasma processing for production of electronic and optical devices, microfluidics for chemical and biologic diagnostics, multistep flow chemistry and separation techniques for on-demand synthesis, and methods for automated synthesis. Jensen was born in Cambridge, UK, and grew up in Copenhagen, Denmark. He graduated from the Technical University of Denmark in 1976 with a M. Sc. degree in Chemical Engineering and received a Ph.D. in chemical engineering from the University of Wisconsin, Madison 1980. At that point, he joined the Department of Chemical Engineering and Materials Science at the University of Minnesota, where he remained on the faculty until 1989, when he joined the Massachusetts Institute of Technology in chemical engineering and materials science and engineering. From 2007- July 2015 he was the Head of the Department of Chemical Engineering. He is a member of the National Academy of Engineering as well as the American Academy of Arts and Science. He is also a Fellow of the American Association for the Advancement of Science (AAAS), and the American Institute of Chemical Engineers, and the Royal Society of Chemistry.Klavs F. Jensen is a chemical engineer recognized for his work on reaction engineering. He is particularly known for his studies of chemical vapor deposition and plasma processing for production of electronic and optical devices, microfluidics for chemical and biologic diagnostics, multistep flow chemistry and separation techniques for on-demand synthesis, and methods for automated synthesis. Jensen was born in Cambridge, UK, and grew up in Copenhagen, Denmark. He graduated from the Technical University of Denmark in 1976 with a M. Sc. degree in Chemical Engineering and received a Ph.D. in chemical engineering from the University of Wisconsin, Madison 1980. At that point, he joined 