VAn isotope geochemist, Jean Jouzel is recognized for his involvement with the reconstruction of past climate changes from ice cores. Since the 1970's, he has actively participated in major ice core international projects. His main scientific expertise is associated with the use of water stable isotopomers and with associated atmospheric modeling using both dynamically simple and General Circulation Models. After obtaining a degree in chemistry, he became involved in isotope geochemistry during his PhD thesis, the aim of which was to derive information about the growth of large hailstones. Since 1968, Jean Jouzel is with the French Alternative Energies and Atomic Energy Commission (CEA) currently as Director of Research (Emeritus) at LSCE (Laboratoire des Sciences du Climat et de l\u2019Environnement). He was head of Institut Pierre Simon Laplace (IPSL), a federative research institute of the Paris area, from 2001 to 2008 and vice chair of the working Group I panel of IPCC from 2002 to 2015. He has been awarded the 2002 Gold CNRS medal, the most prestigious recognition for a French scientist, and the Vetlesen Prize in 2012. In 2016, he has been elected as a foreign associate member of NAS.An isotope geochemist, Jean Jouzel is recognized for his involvement with the reconstruction of past climate changes from ice cores. Since the 1970's, he has actively participated in major ice core international projects. His main scientific expertise is associated with the use of water stable isotopomers and with associated atmospheric modeling using both dynamically simple and General Circulation Models. After obtaining a degree in chemistry, he became involved in isotope geochemistry during his PhD thesis, the aim of which was to derive information about the growth of large hailstones. Since 1968, Jean Jouzel is with the French Alternative Energies and Atomic Energy Commission (CEA) currently as Director of Research (Emeritus) at LSCE (Laboratoire des Sciences du Climat et de l\