VMy field and laboratory research investigates the human impacts of major changes in diet, especially involving the adoption of and increased focus on the production and consumption of domesticated plants, a complex process taking place in the last 10,000 years of human evolution. Human remains from archaeological contexts provide the only direct source for documenting and interpreting changes in diet, health, and quality of life associated with the shift from a lifeway based exclusively on wild plants and animals to a lifeway where virtually every human on the planet today is dependent in some manner on domesticated plants and animals. The research uses biogeochemistry to reconstruct diet and nutrition, mechanobiology to document changes in workload and mobility, and paleopathology of oral and general health to infer exposure to pathogens and other factors that cause physiological stress. Our research from prehistoric settings in North America, Europe, and western Asia reveals a general pattern of declining health and wellbeing and changes in activity, workload, and living circumstances. These health and lifestyle outcomes are linked to the increasing role of plant carbohydrates in diet, living in larger, more densely-settled communities, changing activity patterns and workload, and altering circumstances that promote infectious disease.My field and laboratory research investigates the human impacts of major changes in diet, especially involving the adoption of and increased focus on the production and consumption of domesticated plants, a complex process taking place in the last 10,000 years of human evolution. Human remains from archaeological contexts provide the only direct source for documenting and interpreting changes in diet, health, and quality of life associated with the shift from a lifeway based exclusively on wild plants and animals to a lifeway where virtually every human on the planet today is dependent in some manner on domesticated plants and anima