VMitchell Lazar studies the transcriptional regulation of metabolism. He discovered several nuclear receptors as well as nuclear receptor corepressor complexes containing the chromatin modulating enzyme histone deacetylase 3. Lazar's work has identified molecular mechanisms by which nuclear receptors and corepressors interact with the genome, and how this is controlled in a tissue-specific manner. He has discovered physiological roles of the nuclear receptors and corepressor complexes and the mechanisms by which they function in the epigenome to maintain homeostasis in the face of nutritive, circadian, and temperature challenges. He is especially interested in the circadian nuclear receptor Rev-erb alpha, a key repressive component of the circadian clock that utilizes the corepressor complex to coordinate metabolism and biological rhythms. Lazar has also made seminal discoveries related to PPAR gamma, a nuclear receptor that is a master regulator of adipocyte biology, and a transcriptional link between obesity and insulin resistance. The molecular, cellular, and integrative biology of these factors are being studied in mice and humans. His lab also discovered resistin, a hormone and target of PPAR gamma that is made by fat cells in rodents and by macrophages in humans.Mitchell Lazar studies the transcriptional regulation of metabolism. He discovered several nuclear receptors as well as nuclear receptor corepressor complexes containing the chromatin modulating enzyme histone deacetylase 3. Lazar's work has identified molecular mechanisms by which nuclear receptors and corepressors interact with the genome, and how this is controlled in a tissue-specific manner. He has discovered physiological roles of the nuclear receptors and corepressor complexes and the mechanisms by which they function in the epigenome to maintain homeostasis in the face of nutritive, circadian, and temperature challenges. He is especially interested in the circadian nuclear receptor Rev-erb alph