VMitchell Lazar is an endocrinologist known for his work on the transcriptional regulation of metabolism. Lazar was raised in Syosset on Long Island, received his undergraduate degree in chemistry from MIT. He received his MD and PhD from Stanford University, and trained in Internal Medicine and Endocrinology at Brigham and Women\u2019s Hospital and the Massachusetts General Hospital before joining the University of Pennsylvania faculty in 1989. Lazar's research has uncovered mechanisms by which the environment interacts with the genome to regulate circadian rhythms and metabolism, and how these impact the epidemics of obesity and diabetes. He is currently the Willard and Rhoda Ware Professor in Diabetes and Metabolic Diseases, Founding Director of the Institute for Diabetes, Obesity, and Metabolism and Chief of the Division of Endocrinology, Diabetes, and Metabolism at Penn. Lazar has received awards from numerous international societies and universities, and has been elected to the American Society for Clinical Investigation, the Association of American Physicians, the National Academy of Medicine, the American Academy of Arts and Sciences, and the National Academy of Sciences.Mitchell Lazar is an endocrinologist known for his work on the transcriptional regulation of metabolism. Lazar was raised in Syosset on Long Island, received his undergraduate degree in chemistry from MIT. He received his MD and PhD from Stanford University, and trained in Internal Medicine and Endocrinology at Brigham and Women\u2019s Hospital and the Massachusetts General Hospital before joining the University of Pennsylvania faculty in 1989. Lazar's research has uncovered mechanisms by which the environment interacts with the genome to regulate circadian rhythms and metabolism, and how these impact the epidemics of obesity and diabetes. He is currently the Willard and Rhoda Ware Professor in Diabetes and Metabolic Diseases, Founding Director of the Institute for Diabetes, Obesity, and Met