VLeDoux's research has focused on the brain mechanisms of emotion and memory. He has explored this topic through research on Pavlovian threat (fear) conditioning since the early 1980s.  His work has helped identify the neural circuits and cellular and molecular mechanisms that underlie the acquisition, consolidation, reconsolidation, extinction, and expression of threat conditioning. LeDoux has long argued that the neural mechanisms that detect and respond to threats operate unconsciously, and are distinct from the circuits that give rise to conscious feelings of fear.  The latter, he suggests, can be studied in humans but cannot be studied scientifically in animals.  He argues that using the same term, "fear," to describe circuits that detect and respond to threats and circuits that consciously experience fear is a source of confusion and a hindrance to progress in understand what fear is and how it affects the lives of people.LeDoux's research has focused on the brain mechanisms of emotion and memory. He has explored this topic through research on Pavlovian threat (fear) conditioning since the early 1980s.  His work has helped identify the neural circuits and cellular and molecular mechanisms that underlie the acquisition, consolidation, reconsolidation, extinction, and expression of threat conditioning. LeDoux has long argued that the neural mechanisms that detect and respond to threats operate unconsciously, and are distinct from the circuits that give rise to conscious feelings of fear.  The latter, he suggests, can be studied in humans but cannot be studied scientifically in animals.  He argues that using the same term, "fear," to describe circuits that detect and respond to threats and circuits that consciously experience fear is a source of confusion and a hindrance to progress in understand what fear is and how it affects the lives of people.LeDoux's research has focused on the brain mechanisms of emotion and memory. He has explored this topic through resea