VRon Lesthaeghe\u2019s central interests all focus on structural and cultural changes affecting demographic outcomes in both industrialized and developing countries. More specifically, his expertise pertains to changing patterns of fertility, nuptiality and household formation. His work contains analyses of historical and contemporary European examples, populations of Sub-Sahara Africa, Muslim populations in Europe, and more recently, of Latin American populations. His research on the US concentrates on the links between the outcomes of presidential elections and the fertility and family changes typical of the \u201cSecond Demographic Transition\u201d. In addition, Lesthaeghe has also been a contributor to more technical aspects in demography, such as indirect estimation methods, fertility forcasting, and econometric modelling of the links between aging and social security expenditures .Ron Lesthaeghe\u2019s central interests all focus on structural and cultural changes affecting demographic outcomes in both industrialized and developing countries. More specifically, his expertise pertains to changing patterns of fertility, nuptiality and household formation. His work contains analyses of historical and contemporary European examples, populations of Sub-Sahara Africa, Muslim populations in Europe, and more recently, of Latin American populations. His research on the US concentrates on the links between the outcomes of presidential elections and the fertility and family changes typical of the \u201cSecond Demographic Transition\u201d. In addition, Lesthaeghe has also been a contributor to more technical aspects in demography, such as indirect estimation methods, fertility forcasting, and econometric modelling of the links between aging and social security expenditures .Ron Lesthaeghe\u2019s central interests all focus on structural and cultural changes affecting demographic outcomes in both industrialized and developing countries. More specifically, his expertise per