VLong-lasting activity-dependent changes in the efficacy of synaptic communication play an important role in the development of neural circuits and are critically involved in many forms of learning and memory. Furthermore, pathological disruption of the plasticity of synapses plays an important role in many psychiatric disorders. Therefore elucidating the molecular mechanisms by which these synaptic modifications occur has profound implications for understanding many important brain functions including how future behavior is modified by past experience. Work from my laboratory has demonstrated that there are a variety of related but mechanistically distinct forms of synaptic plasticity. A major goal of my laboratory is to elucidate both the specific molecular events that are responsible for the triggering of these various forms of synaptic plasticity and the exact modifications in synaptic proteins that are responsible for the observed, long-lasting changes in synaptic efficacy. To accomplish this we use cellular electrophysiological recording techniques to examine synaptic plasticity in a variety of different in vitro preparations. We also use molecular techniques to examine the activity-dependent modulation of neurotransmitter receptors and to manipulate synaptic proteins so that their exact functions can be determined. The results of this work have had a major influence on our understanding of the molecular mechanisms underlying learning and memory as well as how disruption in brain plasticity mechanisms contribute to mental illness.Long-lasting activity-dependent changes in the efficacy of synaptic communication play an important role in the development of neural circuits and are critically involved in many forms of learning and memory. Furthermore, pathological disruption of the plasticity of synapses plays an important role in many psychiatric disorders. Therefore elucidating the molecular mechanisms by which these synaptic modifications occur has profound imp