VXiang-Jin Meng (a.k.a. \u201cX.J.\u201d Meng) is a University Distinguished Professor in the Virginia Maryland College of Veterinary Medicine, Virginia Polytechnic Institute and State University (Virginia Tech). He is a virologist recognized for his work on delineating the mechanisms of transmission and pathogenesis of emerging and zoonotic viruses of veterinary and human public health significance. Meng is particularly known for his studies of hepatitis E virus cross-species infection and zoonosis, and vaccine development against economically-important swine viruses such as porcine circovirus type 2 and porcine reproductive and respiratory syndrome virus. Meng was born and grew up in Gaomi, China, and attended Binzhou Medical College where he received his medical degree in 1985. He then entered the graduate program at the Wuhan University College of Medicine (formerly Hubei Medical College), where he received his M.S. in 1988 in Microbiology and Immunology. In 1991, Meng studied at Iowa State University\u2019s College of Veterinary Medicine, where he received his Ph.D. in 1995 in Immunobiology. Following his postdoctoral training in the Laboratory of Infectious Diseases at the National Institutes of Health in Bethesda, Maryland, Meng joined the faculty at Virginia Tech in 1999. Meng was elected to the American Academy of Microbiology in 2012, National Academy of Inventors in 2014, and National Academy of Sciences in 2016.Xiang-Jin Meng (a.k.a. \u201cX.J.\u201d Meng) is a University Distinguished Professor in the Virginia Maryland College of Veterinary Medicine, Virginia Polytechnic Institute and State University (Virginia Tech). He is a virologist recognized for his work on delineating the mechanisms of transmission and pathogenesis of emerging and zoonotic viruses of veterinary and human public health significance. Meng is particularly known for his studies of hepatitis E virus cross-species infection and zoonosis, and vaccine development against economically-imp