VEva Nogales's lab is dedicated to gaining mechanistic insight into two important areas of eukaryotic biology: central dogma machinery in the control of gene expression, and cytoskeleton interactions and dynamics in cell division. To gain a molecular understanding of their systems of interest, her lab uses state-of-the-art cryo-electron microscopy (cryo-EM) and image analysis, as well as biochemical and biophysical assays. Her studies of tubulin and microtubules have shed unique light on the mechanism of microtubule dynamic instability by establishing the structural basis of nucleotide exchange, polymerization-coupled hydrolysis, hydrolysis-induced conformational changes in microtubule structure, taxol binding and stabilization, and the recognition and effect of EB proteins on microtubules. Her lab has also characterized the binding to and self-assembly of Dam1 and Ndc80 kinetochores complexes onto microtubules. Her lab has also contribute significant mechanistic understanding of the eukaryotic transcription initiation process by defining the structure of TFIID and its rearrangement to engage core promoter DNA, and the assembly and structure of the full human transcription preinitiation complex. Additional work from her lab includes the structures of the eukaryotic proteosome, the polycomb repressive complex 2, or a number of CRISPR/Cas complexes and their interaction with target DNA/RNA.Eva Nogales's lab is dedicated to gaining mechanistic insight into two important areas of eukaryotic biology: central dogma machinery in the control of gene expression, and cytoskeleton interactions and dynamics in cell division. To gain a molecular understanding of their systems of interest, her lab uses state-of-the-art cryo-electron microscopy (cryo-EM) and image analysis, as well as biochemical and biophysical assays. Her studies of tubulin and microtubules have shed unique light on the mechanism of microtubule dynamic instability by establishing the structural basis of nucleoti