VEva Nogales uses cryo-electron microscopy to study macromolecular assemblies as whole units of molecular function, by direct visualization of their architecture, functional states, and regulatory interactions. Born in Spain, Nogales studied physics in the Universidad Autónoma de Madrid. She carried out her PhD work at the Synchrotron Radiation Source in the UK with Dr. Joan Bordas using time-resolved small angle scattering to study the assembly of tubulin in the presence of antimitotic drugs. For her postdoctoral work she joined the lab of Dr. Kenneth Downing at Lawrence Berkeley National Laboratory and produced the first atomic structure of tubulin using electron crystallography. In 1998 she joined the Department of Molecular and Cell Biology at UC Berkeley and became a Howard Hughes Medical Investigator in 2000. She is presently Chair of the Biochemistry, Biophysics and Structural Biology Division at UC Berkeley and Senior Faculty Scientist at LBNL. Nogales is the recipient of the Burton Medal by the Microscopy Society (2000), the Chabot Excellence Award (2005), the ASCB Early Career Award (2005), the Dorothy Hodgkin award from the Protein Society (2015) and the Mildred Cohn Award from the ASBMB (2016). She became a member of the National Academy of Sciences in 2015.Eva Nogales uses cryo-electron microscopy to study macromolecular assemblies as whole units of molecular function, by direct visualization of their architecture, functional states, and regulatory interactions. Born in Spain, Nogales studied physics in the Universidad Autónoma de Madrid. She carried out her PhD work at the Synchrotron Radiation Source in the UK with Dr. Joan Bordas using time-resolved small angle scattering to study the assembly of tubulin in the presence of antimitotic drugs. For her postdoctoral work she joined the lab of Dr. Kenneth Downing at Lawrence Berkeley National Laboratory and produced the first atomic structure of tubulin using electron crystallography. In 1998 she joined t