VPlants undergo several major transitions during their post-­embryonic development. Scott Poethig\u2019s laboratory is primarily interested in the first of these transitions, known as vegetative phase change. This transition is marked by changes in a large number of vegetative traits, such as leaf shape and branching patterns, and occurs in all vascular plants. Working first with maize and later with Arabidiopsis, the Poethig laboratory found that vegetative phase change is controlled by a decrease in the expression the evolutionarily conserved microRNAs, miR156/157, resulting in the expression of their targets, SQUAMOSA PROMOTER BINDING (SBP/SPL) transcription factors. They are currently studying the factors responsible for the temporal expression pattern of miR156/157, the mechanism by which these miRNAs repress SBP/SPL gene expression, and the role of miR156/157 in the evolution of shoot morphology in trees.Plants undergo several major transitions during their post-­embryonic development. Scott Poethig\u2019s laboratory is primarily interested in the first of these transitions, known as vegetative phase change. This transition is marked by changes in a large number of vegetative traits, such as leaf shape and branching patterns, and occurs in all vascular plants. Working first with maize and later with Arabidiopsis, the Poethig laboratory found that vegetative phase change is controlled by a decrease in the expression the evolutionarily conserved microRNAs, miR156/157, resulting in the expression of their targets, SQUAMOSA PROMOTER BINDING (SBP/SPL) transcription factors. They are currently studying the factors responsible for the temporal expression pattern of miR156/157, the mechanism by which these miRNAs repress SBP/SPL gene expression, and the role of miR156/157 in the evolution of shoot morphology in trees.Plants undergo several major transitions during their post-­embryonic development. Scott Poethig\u2019s laboratory is primarily interested in the first o