VMy research has focused on the control of molting and metamorphosis in insects by the steroid hormone ecdysone and the sesquiterpenoid juvenile hormone (JH). Ecdysone causes molting as the insect grows, then genetic switching of developmental programs at metamorphosis. Juvenile hormone allows molting but prevents metamorphosis. Our studies using the tobacco hornworm, Manduca sexta, and more recently Drosophila have shown that JH prevents metamorphosis by modulating the turning on and off of a pupal-specifying transcription factor Broad by ecdysone. Broad was also shown to be critical for premetamorphic development in more basal insects with gradual metamorphosis, indicating that Broad plays a key role in the evolution of metamorphosis. We have also shown how these two hormones interact during a larval molt to regulate key enzymes involved in cuticular pigmentation. Most recently we have turned to Drosophila to study the role of JH in the prepupal development of the nervous system showing that it acts a brake to ecdysone-induced premature differentiation. Other interests have been in the neuroendocrine control of behavior, notably our discovery of eclosion hormone that has a key role in initiating insect ecdysis; endocrine interactions between parasitoids and their host; and the discovery of antennal proteins that are involved in odorant transport to the receptor and odorant degradation.My research has focused on the control of molting and metamorphosis in insects by the steroid hormone ecdysone and the sesquiterpenoid juvenile hormone (JH). Ecdysone causes molting as the insect grows, then genetic switching of developmental programs at metamorphosis. Juvenile hormone allows molting but prevents metamorphosis. Our studies using the tobacco hornworm, Manduca sexta, and more recently Drosophila have shown that JH prevents metamorphosis by modulating the turning on and off of a pupal-specifying transcription factor Broad by ecdysone. Broad was also shown to be critical