VAs a hydrologist I have studied the structure of the drainage network of river basins and the fundamental dynamics responsible for its well defined statistical characteristics regardless of geographical location. Thus we have shown that the minimization of a Hamiltonian representing the energy expenditure in the conveyance of water from all sites of the basin to a common outlet leads to networks whose scaling characteristics are identical to those found in natural basins. These so called Optimal Channel Networks are very useful in further studies relating the hydrologic response of a basin to its geomorphological structure. Very much connected to the previous interest have been my studies of the role of the drainage network and other hydrologic drivers on the large scale signatures describing the spatial structure of aquatic biodiversity in river basins. I have also been trying to establish the quantitative links between climate,soil,and vegetation in arid and semiarid regions through the probabilistic structure of soil water content as function of the stochasticity of climate interacting with soil and vegetation characteristics. More recently I have also been involved in the probabilistic characterization of hydroperiods in wetlands as a key mechanism impacting vegetation structure and biodiversity in these ecosystems.As a hydrologist I have studied the structure of the drainage network of river basins and the fundamental dynamics responsible for its well defined statistical characteristics regardless of geographical location. Thus we have shown that the minimization of a Hamiltonian representing the energy expenditure in the conveyance of water from all sites of the basin to a common outlet leads to networks whose scaling characteristics are identical to those found in natural basins. These so called Optimal Channel Networks are very useful in further studies relating the hydrologic response of a basin to its geomorphological structure. Very much connected to the