VThroughout my career I have explored a range of phenomena that play a role in non-optimal judgment and decision making including "belief perseverance," the "false consensus effect," the "hostile media effect," "reactive devaluation," and "naï¿½ve realism." With my colleagues and students I have sought to bring complex real-world phenomena into the laboratory in studies that further our understanding of the strengths and weaknesses that people display as they attempt to understand and influence their social worlds. Work with my long-time collaborators Richard Nisbett and Mark Lepper helped both to identify the overarching "lessons" that emerge as the cumulative contributions of half a century of experimental social psychology -- in particular "situationism," "subjectivism," "equilibration," and the striving to maintain a coherent and positive view of the self -- to forge a bridge between social psychology and the judgment and decision-making tradition in cognitive psychology. My recent work has increasingly focused on sources of interpersonal and intergroup misunderstanding and the psychological barriers that prevent disputants from reaching mutually agreeable improvements over the status quo. I have also sought to apply the lessons from this laboratory research program in real-world efforts at second-track diplomacy and implementation of public peace processes in both Northern Ireland and the Middle East.Throughout my career I have explored a range of phenomena that play a role in non-optimal judgment and decision making including "belief perseverance," the "false consensus effect," the "hostile media effect," "reactive devaluation," and "naï¿½ve realism." With my colleagues and students I have sought to bring complex real-world phenomena into the laboratory in studies that further our understanding of the strengths and weaknesses that people display as they attempt to understand and influence their social worlds. Work with my long-time collaborators Richard Nisbet