VBob Scholes is interested in ecosystem dynamics \u2013 how they respond to internal processes and external perturbations, especially as they approach and transgress limits. The main ecosystems on which he has focussed are savannas, particularly those in Africa. The ecological principles that govern savannas also have application to the global ecosystem as it undergoes unprecedented changes brought about by human actions. Efficient and sensitive ways to monitor ecological change, and methods for determining the sustainability and wise use of the benefits that flow from ecosystems have formed part of this quest.Bob Scholes is interested in ecosystem dynamics \u2013 how they respond to internal processes and external perturbations, especially as they approach and transgress limits. The main ecosystems on which he has focussed are savannas, particularly those in Africa. The ecological principles that govern savannas also have application to the global ecosystem as it undergoes unprecedented changes brought about by human actions. Efficient and sensitive ways to monitor ecological change, and methods for determining the sustainability and wise use of the benefits that flow from ecosystems have formed part of this quest.Bob Scholes is interested in ecosystem dynamics \u2013 how they respond to internal processes and external perturbations, especially as they approach and transgress limits. The main ecosystems on which he has focussed are savannas, particularly those in Africa. The ecological principles that govern savannas also have application to the global ecosystem as it undergoes unprecedented changes brought about by human actions. Efficient and sensitive ways to monitor ecological change, and methods for determining the sustainability and wise use of the benefits that flow from ecosystems have formed part of this quest.
