VI study active earthquake and volcanic process through data collection, inversion, and continuum mechanics modeling. Using sensors such as the Global Positioning System (GPS) and Interferometric Synthetic Aperture Radar (InSAR) my students and I are able to measure deformation of the earth\u2019s surface in space and time and invert these data for the geometry of faults and magma chambers, and spatiotemporal variations in fault slip-rate and magma chamber dilation. In seismically active areas, measurements of strain accumulation, together with appropriate mechanical models of fault systems, are used to place constraints on future seismic hazard. In volcanic areas, magma rising through the earth\u2019s crust also deforms the earth surface in ways that can be used to constrain eruptive potential. We use these observational constraints to develop and test physical models of active plate boundaries such as the San Andreas Fault, and the Cascade subduction zone, the nucleation of earthquakes, slow slip events, and the physics of magma migration leading to volcanic eruptions. I have also analyzed pore-fluid effects on faulting, and shown that poro-elastic stressing can explain earthquakes induced by fluid extraction.I study active earthquake and volcanic process through data collection, inversion, and continuum mechanics modeling. Using sensors such as the Global Positioning System (GPS) and Interferometric Synthetic Aperture Radar (InSAR) my students and I are able to measure deformation of the earth\u2019s surface in space and time and invert these data for the geometry of faults and magma chambers, and spatiotemporal variations in fault slip-rate and magma chamber dilation. In seismically active areas, measurements of strain accumulation, together with appropriate mechanical models of fault systems, are used to place constraints on future seismic hazard. In volcanic areas, magma rising through the earth\u2019s crust also deforms the earth surface in ways that can be u