VMy first significant piece of work is the result that a finitely generated projective module in the polynomial ring in two variables over a field is free,(the first progress in a conjecture of Serre, which was settled later by Quillen and independently Suslin). A substantial part of my work is in the field of \u005cmoduli of vector bundles" and is inspired by the work of Andrre Weil and David Mumford. It gives, in particular, the basic constructions of the \u005cmoduli spaces" of vector bundles on curves. They are projective varieties and their underlying topological spaces are given by unitary representations of the fundamental group of the curve. The latter is joint work with M.S.Narasimhan and marked the beginning of all this work. For the construction of these moduli spaces in arbitrary characteristic, one needs a conjecture of Mumford on representations of semi-simple groups. I proved this conjecture for the linear group GL(2). Subsequently, I gave a quotient space approach to solve this conjecture and a key idea in this method led to an ampleness criterion for line bundles on projective varieties and led to what are called \u005cSeshadri constants". The conjecture was settled later by Haboush and recently I perceive that my quotient space approach can be made to work. My work on Standard Monomial Theory (SMT) is inspired by a classical work of Hodge and aims to give nice bases of finite dimensional representations of semi-simple groups and more generally of sections of \u005cdominant" line bundles on \u005cSchubert varieties". SMT gives a character formula which is, in spirit, quite diferent from the Weyl character formula and provides a tool for the geometric study of Schubert varieties. I succeeded in doing this only for the classical groups (most of my work is in collaboration with V. Lakshmibai and C. Musili) and later Peter Littelmann succeeded in doing it for any semi-simple group.My first significant piece of work is the result that a finitely generate