VMichael F. Summers is a chemist recognized for his work on the structural biology of retroviruses. He is known particularly for his applications of NMR spectroscopy to the structural proteins and viral RNA genome of HIV-1, as well as for his work with minorities and development of approaches for inclusive excellence in STEM. Dr. Summers was raised mainly in Florida, spending summers working his grandparents dairy farm in Wisconsin. He received his BS in chemistry in 1980 from the University of West Florida, his Ph.D. in 1984 from Emory University, and was a postdoctoral fellow at the NIH from 1984-1987. He joined the faculty at the University of Maryland Baltimore County in 1987 and has been an Investigator with the Howard Hughes Medical Institute since 1994. Dr. Summers is a recipient of the Protein Society Young Investigator Award, ASBMB Ruth Kirschstein Award, the Carl Branden Award of the Protein Society, the Emily M. Gray Mentoring Award of the Biophysical Society, the ASBMB Award for Exemplary Contributions to Education, the Mentor Award of the American Association for the Advancement of Science, American Society for Microbiology Hinton Award for Mentoring, and the White House Presidential Award for Science, Mathematics and Engineering Mentoring.Michael F. Summers is a chemist recognized for his work on the structural biology of retroviruses. He is known particularly for his applications of NMR spectroscopy to the structural proteins and viral RNA genome of HIV-1, as well as for his work with minorities and development of approaches for inclusive excellence in STEM. Dr. Summers was raised mainly in Florida, spending summers working his grandparents dairy farm in Wisconsin. He received his BS in chemistry in 1980 from the University of West Florida, his Ph.D. in 1984 from Emory University, and was a postdoctoral fellow at the NIH from 1984-1987. He joined the faculty at the University of Maryland Baltimore County in 1987 and has been an Investigator with the H