VJeremy Thorner's research at UC Berkeley has utilized budding yeast (Saccharomyces cerevisiae) as a model eukaryote in which to elucidate fundamental molecular mechanisms in the organization, specificity, fidelity, and regulation of signal transduction processes. He has made path-finding contributions to our understanding of peptide hormone biogenesis and action, calcium ion and calcium-binding proteins, G protein-coupled receptors and the signaling cascades they initiate, mitogen-activated protein kinase modules and other protein kinase networks, and production and mobilization of phosphoinositides. He has also focused on the biochemical basis of the cellular responses evoked by these pathways. Of particular interest to him has been how extracellular stimuli control gene expression, cell growth and division, and cell differentiation, especially changes in membrane dynamics, cytoskeletal structure and cell morphology. The work carried out by his laboratory has always employed a productive blend of molecular genetics, biochemical analysis, and cell imaging methods. Furthermore, in these studies, Thorner's laboratory has demonstrated that the functions of the genes and gene products discovered first in yeast, a unicellular microbe, are highly conserved and thus have provided seminal understanding of biological processes that are broadly applicable to multicellular organisms, including humans.Jeremy Thorner's research at UC Berkeley has utilized budding yeast (Saccharomyces cerevisiae) as a model eukaryote in which to elucidate fundamental molecular mechanisms in the organization, specificity, fidelity, and regulation of signal transduction processes. He has made path-finding contributions to our understanding of peptide hormone biogenesis and action, calcium ion and calcium-binding proteins, G protein-coupled receptors and the signaling cascades they initiate, mitogen-activated protein kinase modules and other protein kinase networks, and production and mobilization 