VAs a physical/analytical chemist, I have studied the fundamental interactions of light with adsorbed molecules on metal surfaces that support surface plasmons. This area of research, now known as plasmonics, led to the discovery of surface-enhanced Raman spectroscopy (SERS). The key observable in SERS is the greatly amplified intensity of Raman scattering, as much as one billion times, when the localized surface plasmons resonances (LSPR) of Ag or Au nanoparticles are excited. Through detailed studies of the mechanism of SERS on structurally well-defined nanoparticles, it has been established that the enhancement of Raman scattering and, indeed, all optically driven processes is mainly caused by the local electromagnetic fields that surround excited nanoparticles. This discovery enabled me to develop of a broad spectrum of new analytical methods applied to problems in chemical and biological sensing to electrochemistry, materials science, ultrahigh vacuum surface science, and even to art conservation science. Recent work centers on the exploration of single molecule/single nanoparticle spectroscopy. One major goal is the development of ultrahigh vacuum, low temperature tip-enhanced Raman spectroscopy (TERS). TERS potentially combines the single molecule sensitivity of surface-enhanced Raman spectroscopy (SERS) with the atomic scale spatial resolution of the STM.As a physical/analytical chemist, I have studied the fundamental interactions of light with adsorbed molecules on metal surfaces that support surface plasmons. This area of research, now known as plasmonics, led to the discovery of surface-enhanced Raman spectroscopy (SERS). The key observable in SERS is the greatly amplified intensity of Raman scattering, as much as one billion times, when the localized surface plasmons resonances (LSPR) of Ag or Au nanoparticles are excited. Through detailed studies of the mechanism of SERS on structurally well-defined nanoparticles, it has been established that the enhanc