VStephen West\u2019s laboratory is interested in the mechanisms of DNA double strand break repair by homologous recombination. His research focuses on the identification and characterization of recombination repair proteins, and how they promote genome stability. He is known for his elucidation of the mechanisms by which recombination intermediates are processed to allow the separation of sister chromatids at mitosis. In particular, he identified nucleases that resolve four-way DNA junctions (Holliday junctions) and showed that these enzymes are essential for chromosome segregation. These nucleases were found to be tightly regulated in S-phase cells, and become active later in the cell cycle where they ensure the resolution of sister chromatid bridges. His work has important implications for the relationships between genome instability and cancer.Stephen West\u2019s laboratory is interested in the mechanisms of DNA double strand break repair by homologous recombination. His research focuses on the identification and characterization of recombination repair proteins, and how they promote genome stability. He is known for his elucidation of the mechanisms by which recombination intermediates are processed to allow the separation of sister chromatids at mitosis. In particular, he identified nucleases that resolve four-way DNA junctions (Holliday junctions) and showed that these enzymes are essential for chromosome segregation. These nucleases were found to be tightly regulated in S-phase cells, and become active later in the cell cycle where they ensure the resolution of sister chromatid bridges. His work has important implications for the relationships between genome instability and cancer.Stephen West\u2019s laboratory is interested in the mechanisms of DNA double strand break repair by homologous recombination. His research focuses on the identification and characterization of recombination repair proteins, and how they promote genome stability. He is known for his 